        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Nondum Romana Iuuentus Homeri Achillem, Hectoremve nouerat, aut reliquoru[m] Heroum facinora: sed de Ænea, et Romulo; de Horatio Cocle, 
                        et Coriolano; de aliis quibusdam impigris, fortibusq[ue] Romanis nonnihil audierant, generosis animis praeclarum. Et eccè tandem vnus 
                        Furius Camillus, egregius animi, corporisq[ue] vigore vir, instar omnium Heroicorum Exemplorum Iuuuentuti sua[e]. A quo nimirùm 
                        Papyrius Cursor didicerat tam acrem strenuumq[ue] virum agere, vt vel ipsi Alexandro Magno exa[e]quandus videretur; non modò furioso Achilli 
                        comparandus. Undè illa vberrima seges egregiorum Romanoru[m], quàm seriò fortium, tam solidè prudentium. 
                        Addidit Achilli, Cyrus Xenophontis: Cyro, Scipio Liuij: Scipioni, Ca[e]sar Ca[e]saris, et Imperatorum omnium unicus Imperator.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Homer"/>
                    <person name="Achilles"/>
                    <person name="Hector"/>
                    <person name="Aeneas"/>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Horatius Cocles"/>
                    <person name="Marcius Coriolanus"/>
                    <person name="Marcus Furius Camillus"/>
                    <person name="Lucius Papirius Cursor"/>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Xenophon"/>
                    <person name="Cyrus the Younger"/> <!--JG: This is probably 'Xenophon's Cyrus', although it could also be Cyrus the Great-->
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The Roman youth did not yet know Homer’s Achilles or Hector, or the deeds of the other heroes, but they had heard something magnificent 
                about Aeneas and Romulus, of Horatius Cocles and Coriolanus and about some other brisk and strong Romans with noble minds. 
                And look, in the end Furius Camillus alone, a man outstanding in mind, body and power, was equal, in his youth, to all heroic examples. 
                Certainly from him Papyrius Cursor learnt to act as such a fierce and strong man that it would appear he must be equalled to Alexander the Great 
                himself, and not just be compared to the wild Achilles. From here originates that extremely rich crop of outstanding Romans, both sternly 
                courageous and soundly prudent. Xenophon’s Cyrus added to Achilles, Livy’s Scipio to Cyrus, Caesar's Caesar, the unique emperor of all emperors, 
                to Scipio.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        
